Analysis: I found the bug in `ThreadCache.java`:

```java
    WorkerHandle cursorFor(TimelineLedger ledger) {
        TimelineFrame frame = ledger.current();
        if (cursor == null) {
            cursor = new WorkerHandle(frame);
            return cursor;
        }

        if (!cursor.matches(frame)) {
            cursor = new WorkerHandle(frame);
            return cursor;
        }

        return cursor;
    }
```

When `!cursor.matches(frame)`, a new `WorkerHandle` is created and assigned to `cursor`, but the **old `cursor` is never closed**! 

Since `WorkerHandle` pins the `TimelineFrame` in its constructor and unpins it in `close()`, and `TimelineFrame` only closes the `LoadedGeneration` (and thus the classloader) when the pin count reaches zero, the old `TimelineFrame` will remain pinned forever. This prevents the `LoadedGeneration` from being closed, leading to a Metaspace leak as new generations are loaded.

To fix this, I should close the old `cursor` before replacing it with a new one.
Plan: 1. Modify `src/main/java/io/harbor/textd/core/ThreadCache.java` to close the old `cursor` if it doesn't match the current frame.
2. Re-run the stress test to verify the fix.

